			</div>

	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1246032" style="border-right: 1px solid #D1D1E1">
	
		
		

		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1246032"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				*nods at Torcer*<br />
And the Jewish food/hygiene laws were, to a fair extent, based on sound health concerns for *those times*. For example, pigs really are dangerous to your health: they tend to have nasty parasites and are how the 'Flu jumps to Man. <br />
But, how could you explain that thousands of years ago to simple folk? They could not cope with that, thus, it's declared &quot;a sin&quot; and fear of the Big Eye In the Sky, rather than common sense/understanding, keeps them healthier.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>It&#8217;s true that the Kosher Laws are based upon sound reasons, as most religious rules are, but it&#8217;s also true that the reasons don&#8217;t have to be good for the Orthodox to follow the rule.  Indeed, the easiest way for an ancient society to codify important social rules was to dress it up in divine commandments.  Many of these rules were particular to pastoral and/or agrarian societies and don&#8217;t translate well into Post Industrial societies (e.g., Ceiling Cat sez no make wit da teh gey sex), while some rules are timeless (e.g., Thou Shall Not Kill).    <br />
<br />
One difference between kosher laws, other than one still makes some scientific sense (Surely you all saw &#8220;Airplane!&#8221;), and the blood transfusion is that there&#8217;s nothing expressly and unambiguously prohibiting blood transfusion in the Bible, you could compare that biblical exegesis that results in the No mixing Dairy and Meat with the exegesis re: blood transfusions (Not surprisingly, the no mixing Dairy and Meat has no public health purpose like the literal biblical text does).  Fundamentalists, for their entire adherence to the supposed literal text, often apply rules that are questionable textual interpretations.<br />
<br />
 <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Arbitrarily, slicing off a baby's foreskin is also a moral decision based on health considerations from millenia ago, but it's still pretty common today. In a couple hundred years I wonder if our descendants will see some news piece on some kid who was mutilated during circumcision and have the same reaction we're having today to this story.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>I&#8217;d argue that scientific data about how circumcision can help combat things like HIV demonstrates that the ancients were onto something.  In any event, all religious rules, including circumcision, should be questioned.  If there&#8217;s a good reason to continue with a rule, or it is harmless, then continue to follow it, if not, we should toss it into the dustbin as an artifact of a pre-industrial society.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		
